FIG. 1 illustrates a conventional hollow insertion needle and hook wire;


FIG. 2 illustrates the hook wire of FIG. I inserted into the insertion needle with the barb extending through the opening in the insertion needle;


FIG. 3 is an overall view of a localization assembly made according to the invention with the anchor in a radially expanded, deployed condition;


FIG. 4 is a partial cross-sectional view of the distal portion of the localization device of FIG. 2 with the anchor in a radially contracted configuration;


FIG. 5 illustrates the localization device of FIG. 4 with the anchor moved to a radially expanded configuration by the movement of the distal ends of the outer sleeve member and the inner wire member towards one another;


FIG. 5A is a cross-sectional view taken along line 5A--5A of FIG. 5;


FIG. 6 illustrates a further embodiment of the localization device of FIG. 4 in which the inner wire member has been replaced by an inner shaft member having a pointed distal end to potentially eliminate the need for the delivery needle of FIG. 3;


FIG. 7 illustrates the device of FIG. 6 with the anchor in a first radially expanded condition, the anchor forming a somewhat flattened spherical shape;


FIG. 8 illustrates the localization device of FIG. 7 with the anchor in a fully radially expanded configuration in the shape of a generally flat disk, the anchor illustrated positioned on the far side of a lesion or other target tissue;


FIG. 9 illustrates an alternative embodiment of the localization assembly of FIG. 3 in which the localization device of FIG. 3 has been replaced by a localization device having an inner shaft member and an outer shaft member, the outer shaft member having a series of longitudinally extending slits formed at its distal end;


FIG. 10 illustrates the localization device of FIG. 9 with the inner shaft member pulled relative to the outer sleeve member causing the sleeve segments to expand radially to form a Malecot-type anchor; and


FIG. 11 illustrates a further alternative embodiment of the invention in which the anchor is in the form of an expandable balloon, the balloon mounted to the distal end of a shaft, the balloon-type anchor and distal shaft end housed within a delivery needle;


FIG. 11A illustrates the embodiment of FIG. 11 which the balloon-type anchor is in its radially-contracted condition and is positioned past the sharpened tips of the delivery needle; and


FIG. 11B illustrates the shaft and balloon-type anchor of FIG. 11A with the balloon-type anchor in its radially-expanded, deployed condition.
